segments.text: Schools, we were going crazy with schools.
We were building everywhere.

You'll notice the schools are named after people, named after the early teachers in the community or the school board, but we were building as fast as we could get them up because the community was growing that way.
Let's see, what else happened?
Fabulous, fabulous.
I'll have to think on it.
We'll go on and on.
If I think of something, I'll jump back at you.
Okay.
Pasadena has had a reputation for many years for being a white community.
Has the Palmoy family seen or experienced any changes in race relations in Pasadena?
Well, in not the...
typical sense that you would think of race relations in Pasadena.
Pasadena, in its early days, was, like I said, a settlement of farmers.
And you had Spanish Mexicans living in the area at the time being basically dirt farmers themselves.
And they worked with the local farmers.
And so there's always been a contingency of Mexicans in, or Spanish surname, as it were,
in the community of Pasadena.
They've never been very visible.
They have very well hung to themselves.
Most of their...
They lived off of...
They lived out in then the country, but as the community grew, they concentrated somewhat around the Red Bluff area.
I know in the 40s, late 40s, early 50s, when I was involved in the church myself, we had a mission.
We established a Spanish mission out on...
and I'd go out there and do the little programs and we'd do Christmas programs with them and things like that.
So there was an interaction between them, but there was still a separation.
Went to school with some Spanish people.
I knew them, they knew me, we talked, but we didn't socialize together.
Most people think in terms of race relations as being black relations.
That didn't exist in Pasadena, never has.
I have a listing of people who signed up for the draft in 1914 in Pasadena.
And there were two blacks out of about 35 people, Negro.
I assumed they would be Negro farmers.
That was probably the highest percentages of blacks that we had ever had in the community.
In 1960, Pasadena's population was 89,000.
we had 45 blacks.
In 1980, passing the population is 112,000.
We have 950 blacks within the community.
So there is, blacks are not visible in the community.
First, there's not being enough of them.
So we never really had that as a race issue.
We are having a race,
Well, you go back to the Hispanics and finish that side off.
Hispanics have always had their community, as I have said.
And as the integration, both legal and illegal, from Mexico
accelerated in the last 10 years in Mexico, particularly during the boom days of the last five years.
They found a section over here in Pasadena.

The two main concentrations of Hispanics in Harris County are on the east side of downtown Houston, one being in the eastern section of Houston and one being the relatively small barrio in the Pasadena area.
They're used, they work in industry.
basically non-managerial levels because most of them are not educated.
They go through the school systems.
But they have, and they have in the local community, begun to take some roles and responsibilities.
We have quite a few Spanish doctors, attorneys.
I don't know about the CPAs.
We've had from time to time some Spanish involved in government.
Spanish, probably proportionally-wise, a balanced percentage in civic organizations.

Never really been, there's never been a racial clash in Pasadena, whether it be Spanish, Negro, Black, or a problem today, I think it is a problem, or the growing concern is the Asian community in Pasadena.
Pasadena is one of us, and it's sort of a settlement area for the Asian.
It's felt strongly in the school district.
the school district has had an increase in Asians in the last, well, I don't know what it is here in the 80s, but it's something like it doubles every year as far as the Asian population.
The Spanish population has grown significantly, or has grown significantly, but it's not as much of a teaching problem as it is for the Asians in the community.
as it appears to be typical with the race, are very industrious, hard-working people.
I think every 7-Eleven in town is all about Asian.
They've got businesses in the community.
There's no confrontation with them.
So there's no, there's been no problems.
It's, each have their own area, but there's no conflict over it.
How did your parents and family feel about blacks?
And did they support the Brown versus Board decision in 1954?
Well, when I was in college, I was asked by a black, you know, well, gee, you don't appear to be, you know, the prejudiced type person I'd expect from the South.
I said, well, until I got to college, I didn't know what black was.
Said earlier, there really wasn't any in Pasadena.
Not until the late 50s, when there became some nationwide agitation, was there any visibility of blacks in Houston.
And that was the only place I had contact with, was Blacksville.
I'd go into Houston.
Never had the discussion with my parents, or my grandparents, or my great grandparents.
I've never had a discussion with any of them about blacks because we never had that type of contact.
So you wouldn't talk about, well, how do you feel about Russians if you've never met a Russian?
Or how do you feel about someone from Afghanistan?
It just wasn't a question that was raised in the test and discussed and talked about.
The KKK is located in Pasadena.
But it's not the Pasadena blacks that they're working against, because there are so few blacks.
The only agitations that KKK causes are all outside of Pasadena.
It just happens to be an available building in Pasadena.
Probably a lot of the guys work out of the industrial plants, and so a convenient place.
The thing is open, I think, once a month.
And when they take on the Asians, as they've done,
down what was tripping boats and all that stuff.
It's always outside of the community.
For Brown versus Board of Education, again, that's another thing that really didn't have an application in the community because we didn't have separate facilities.
If there was a black in the community, it went to Pasadena.
If there was brown in the community, if there were yellow, whatever your color was, you went to the schools.
We didn't have any buses.
The buses only went one way.
It was from your home to the school.
And we did, you know, there was only up until, let's see, there was only one high school until the late 50s.
I think 57 was probably the first year for South Houston.
Rayburn didn't come until the 60s.
Elementary schools was in your neighborhood, and they're still strong of Asher and Oberlin.
That's where you go.
So we've missed out on all the fun.
busing, riots in the street, those types of things.
Houston didn't have those problems in the early days of the turmoil as it were.
The blacks in Houston reported that they had their own lifestyles, their own way of life, like the Asians do now in Houston.
And they weren't looking for any additional territory.
They were entitled to it, but they weren't really looking for it.
So they sent blacks in from out of town.
I wrote the headlines in the city, or in the newspapers, was that the local blacks met the out-of-town blacks at the bus station and said, you get back on the bus.
They said, look, we had some agitation in Houston, but it was, like I said, that was the only contact that I had with it, and this is well into the 60s when we were separated.
Was Pasadena ever affected by segregation, busing, or the civil rights issues?
I seem to anticipate that question.
No.
I don't think I can really elaborate much more than that.
I'm sure that there's an undertone.
I know Pasadena has a reputation of being a lowly white town.
Supposedly, you didn't, if you were black, you didn't stay in Pasadena after dark.
South Houston had a sign over there.
There were a thing that said, blacks don't let the sun set on you.
But South Houston, when George Christie moved his circus there in the late 20s, he said, hey,
I've got all sorts of people working for me.
That sign comes down, or I don't move in the town.
The sign came down.
Now, perhaps the attitude remained, but it was sort of an unwritten law.
That was the case.
I know even today, blacks feel that way about Pasadena.
But we've got blacks in the police department.
We've got blacks working in businesses all over town.
We're still perceived that way, and I'm sure it exists, but it's not on any covert, noticeable level.
We don't talk about it in meetings.
Nobody makes any jokes about it.
It's not the pun or anything.
We talk about Aggies.
Have racial attitudes changed over the four generations of the Pomeroy family?
I'm sure that attitudes have changed, and they've changed because of enlightenment.
If you didn't have contact with these people, then you couldn't form an opinion.
And any opinion you had is probably something you either heard or you read about.
As you become involved with these people, I think probably your first reaction is, you know, these are strange people.
I don't like this.
Because this is an extremely conservative community.
It's still got very much of worrying roots.
We're still perceived as a redneck type community.
But we've been placed in contact with a few more blacks.
Our children are going to school with a few blacks.
And these aren't agitation experiences.
These are just students in the classroom.
It's like when I went to school with the Mexicans, there was no agitation.
They were decent people.
And as you get to meet more and more, your feelings towards them
improve, change, accept them more, and I'm confident that we're much more tolerant, much more enlightened than we were back in 1900, and I'm sure we have a ways to go.
Has the Pomeroy family ever been involved in the government of Pasadena?
Pomeroy's per se, as Pomeroy's, none.
The extended family, as I've mentioned earlier, yes, we were involved.
It's sort of like a, you know, well, you take care of that area, and we'll take care of this area of the community.
The Williams side of the family were involved in politics with Everett Williams.
He was the city councilman, the city commissioner at the time, head of the water department.
Clyde McMaster made his contribution as mayor for eight years.
My grandfather...
When they were building, one of the schools here in town, Howard Telps, actually senior, the father that Howard Telps and most of us think of today, was the contractor.
He was living in the rented room in my grandfather's house.
My grandfather said, gee, one day I'd like to be mayor of Pasadena.
And Telps wrote a book, and it's in the book, okay?
John was the type of person that he wasn't going to stop the politics.
He had to work on his job, and when he got through with his job, then he would do his community service.
And the first one was the church.
They never quite got to government, which is fine.
I've been tempted myself to be involved in government, but I've decided there's other areas I can make contributions.
I don't need to...
kiss babies and shake a lot of hands.
How has the women's role in Pasadena society changed throughout your family's history?
Well, women have always played a fairly significant role in the community.
With the farming beginnings, there was no differentiation.
If you had a pair of hands, you were working.
You were a husband, you were a wife, you were children.
It didn't make any difference.
As long as you could hold your diapers up, you went out and did a job.
The first postmaster in Pasadena was a male.
The second postmaster was female.
And in the first 30 years, the postmaster mistresses in Pasadena, most of them were female.
The first one of those was also the first woman attorney.
She went off, got her education, came back, was an attorney in town.
This is all pre-1930.
My great-grandmother, Anna Louise Fonroy,
was an agitator type or something, I guess you could say.

And when Pasadena incorporated in 1924, decided we needed some city services and stuff, we made the mistake of incorporating Houston Light and Power Facility on the Houston Ship Channel, and crowned the final Houston Ship Channel.
Well, this just infuriated Houston, because Houston spent all this time promoting a ship channel, and here's these little towns coming in,
grab ahold of all this big tax base.
So they sued Pasadena.
They got the Secretary of State to turn state attorney to sue Pasadena.
I don't know what the grounds were particularly.
But anyway, Pasadena got scared off and said, OK, well, we can't afford to fight the big state and the big city.
So they backed off and incorporated the following year.
Houston got to thinking, well, I bet those rabble-rousers are just guessing.
Those rabble-rousers are going to do it again.
So why don't we incorporate them?
They're not incorporating them.
Annex them.
So they jumped out and annexed Harrisburg, which is between Houston and Pasadena.
They started looking at territory outside of there.
And my great-grandmother said, no, we don't want to be part of Houston.
We want to be Pasadena.
So she organized a local community, and they put up a fight in the end of Houston, called the City Council.
She went and talked to Sinclair, now Arco,
And they said, no, you know, we agree with you.
So they provided the attorneys for Pasadena, and we went into Houston and fought off their annexation attempts, and turned right around and reincorporated.
So in 1929, we were incorporated as a city, and we've continued as a city since then.
First legal, I'm sorry, first medical profession
started in Pasadena in 1937.
Prior to that, we'd have a doctor, and when he would die, another doctor would come into town, and that type of thing.

In 1937, Dr. Edward Connors moved to Pasadena, built a hospital, which was the first hospital in the area, and started bringing some of his buddies in from Oklahoma, where he graduated from medical school.
And it was just like, no sooner they got in, they got drafted.
So we had doctors coming in and doctors coming out,
And somebody had a really great idea and brought in a lady doctor about 1939.
Of course, she didn't get drafted.
So the first female doctor that passed in was about 1939.
She was here for like about five years and then left.
And in the chiropractic profession, I think they had passed in in 1942 and two of them were female chiropractors.
And one of them, Dr. Sally Allen, is still here.
She's still in business.
The doctors that were here originally are now retired, but Sally Allen is still a chiropractor.

Education, the first, it was quite a few years before we had a lady on the board of education, board of directors or whatever it is, and I'm not sure we have had any females other than that, but in the education business, they have been involved, of course, as teachers, 99%.
The early teachers were women.
I said, I think we married half of them in the Palmer family.
No sooner than the schools got started than the PTA got started.
And passing the PTA or its roots is probably
Well, it is the oldest civic organization in the community.
And it was formed by the ladies.
It was run by the ladies.
You don't have a few men, but it's usually the mothers that are concerned.
It's still a dynamic force shaping the education of the community.
Business-wise, they were involved, as I said, equally with men.
There was no real discrimination.
A few of them, although their husbands worked with them, it was known as their business.
Betty Mitchell is one example.
Her father, Walter Williams, started a grocery store and a dry goods.
And his daughter, Betty, married Mr. Mitchell, and she ran the store.
He opened up another store and said, no, I'll take it back.
No, no, no.
It was their children that started opening that grocery store.
But she was known as Betty Mitchelson.
We had several ladies that had clothing stores in town.
So they were fairly visible.
They were fairly involved.
When it came to industry, however, they were not involved.
That was a men's business.
And it hadn't been until the last 10 years or so that they had really gotten involved.
I think it's sort of...

hysterical or funny or ironic or something, but I was talking to a savings owner, a company president a couple years ago, and he says, well, we were talking about Pasadena having the second highest per household income in the state of Texas.
We've got a strong industry base over here.
They pay good.
There's good overtime.
We've always had a lot of two-member family employment.
And he'll say,
Well, you take one situation I was dealing with the other day.
The husband is an insurance salesman.
He's making about $15,000.
Now, his wife, she's a welder.
She works out at Sheff.
She makes $25,000 a year.
So I'm sure we've had some domestic problems over the wife making more money, but they pretty well carry their weight.
Oh, one more thing was the city government
We have had several ladies serve on city council, and we've got a bunch running now.
They've gotten more and more excited.
They're going to come out of the school system.
So it's evolving, and I think they, from my perspective, are getting a good fair share.
Pasadena has changed tremendously over the years, but it seems to be impossible in changing its Wild West image.
Is Pasadena really the Wild West?
Well, no, we're east of Houston, actually.
Maybe we're the Wild East.
Now, Pasadena has the image from our local major entertainment attraction, which is Gillies.
And Mickey Gilear, when he's on national TV, and they say, and Mickey Gilear from Houston, he says, no, I'm from Pasadena.
He's proud of it, which is a blessing on one side and a problem on the other side.
Because no place else on national TV does someone stand up as a conductor of a symphony, as a movie star, as a president of the United States, and say, I'm from Pasadena.
So the image nationally people have of Pasadena is Gillies.
It's just marketing.
They know how to market their product, and the rest of the community hasn't marketed its product.
As I like to point out, maybe 2,000, maybe 5,000 people in Pasadena go to Gillies.
There's 120 other thousand people in Pasadena.
What do they do?
More of them go to church, but nationally we're not going for our churches.
More of them go to school.
We've got a good reputation.
We have much less that go to our new Philharmonic Orchestra, but we're hoping to build that.
We've had a little theater that's been in existence long before Gillies, but they haven't been able to market themselves as well.
So you only have maybe 1,000 people that have ever gone to a little theater versus the 2,000 a weekend that goes to Gillies.
One of the things that people point to as our Wally West image is our alter ego horses, our pickup trucks.
Well, we've got pickup trucks.
You're right about that.
But we don't have horses in the back of our pickup trucks.
What we've got is we've got welding equipment.
We've got construction tools.
We've got a trailer hitch we put our boat on or mulch for our gardens.
There's a lot of things we use our pickup trucks for.
I would be surprised if the average in Pasadena is not a two-car family.
Maybe a three-car family.
And the wife, as is typical, has the nice sedan or maybe the station wagon because she holds the children with her.
And then the husband, because he goes into industry, well, there's two things.
You don't take a nice car out of the industry because, you know, the chemicals from the air were rusted on the spot.
So you take a work vehicle.
And that works not only to get you there, but also puts you around the house.
Because we're a lot of do-it-ourselvers around here.
Do-it-yourself is very good.
I finally had to borrow a trailer.
I don't have a pickup truck, but I need to haul things around.
So we've got that problem, yes.
And it's a matter, we've got to work on promoting the community, the family time, the churches, the education, the residential areas.
People are amazed, constantly, at the residential areas in Pasadena.
If you go into

Deer Park, and you go down to Clear Lake, and you go to some of the other areas, you've got a lot of major tract builders, U.S. owned general homes, violence, and all of those, which are basically Cooke's Cove type homes.
Pasadena, you have tremendous amount of custom built homes.
You've got a few local builders, and they build only in the Pasadena market.
There's not that, they don't use a total of 10 home plans.
You probably have 2,000 different home styles out of the 10,000 homes we have in Pasadena.
Newer areas are just a collage of architectural styles.
You don't have a subdivision of Cape Cod.
You've got a street that's got a pictorial, and a Cape Cod, and a colonial, and a modern, and a you name it, it's there.
We even have long cabins in Pasadena.
You've got an image of being a redneck, a hard hat, a long neck community.
Well, we do.
Pittsburgh does too.
I was listening to a news report the other day, and they said, yeah, Pittsburgh was all upset about being called a redneck city.
Redneck is, you know, you started out with the little sun on your neck because you worked outside.
Most of the people in Pasadena, well, take that back.
The last couple of years, the last couple of decades, the census report shows that outside construction, manual labor is a significantly small, is an insignificantly small.
Well, however it works, it's a small number.
Most of our people are managers out in the plants.
We've got so much automation, most everybody's a supervisor or manager.
And they're pulling down $35,000, $50,000, $65,000 a year.
We've got the largest single employer within the state of New Mexico, and it's the school district.
Second largest, I think, is in the conversation.
Maybe through the government.
The shift from a redneck to a person who's unwilling to change and accept new ideas, I think it's basically unfair on the community.
I don't see ourselves as not being open to change and being stuck in the old dog-run past.
The average age in Pasadena is about 27.
So that means that you've got a lot of young people in the community.
And they're open, one with television, one with, I think everyone in high school now has a car.
Mobility in the community, I think it's an unfair label for the community.
I think our biggest problem is that we're not marketing what we have, both to people in the community, so they're proud of their community, and to people outside.
We've invited lately some of the media in the community to say, hey, let's show you things that you're not running in town filming and leaving, because the KKK are meeting, or
city governments handed this big squabble, or a big narcotics fight.
So let's show you some of the things about what really is the essence, what we feel the essence of.
What has been your role in improving Pasadena's cultural image?
Well, I can characterize my participation, I guess, in two different ways.
I was introduced a while back at a speech I was giving on medical history in Pasadena.
Dr. Parker Williams, the president of St. Justin College South, got up there and said, I'd like to introduce David Pommoy, a has-been.
He has been, I think, everything.
My wife, on the other hand, characterizes me half-jokingly and very seriously as a civic junkie.
I just can't say no.
And if someone says, gee, David, I think what we need in Pasadena is this and such, key words, need in Pasadena.
I'll say, right, and here, I'll do this.
So I've suffered from the inability to say no, and it has gotten me into a fair amount of trouble.
I've been involved in promoting what I call the hometown image of Pasadena.
As I had said earlier, so many people came to Pasadena, I'm going to make the money, I'm going to leave, but they're still here.
In fact, I've talked to numerous ones of the third generation, that that's what they were going to do.
Come and go, and now they have children, and their children are now in Pasadena growing up.
And when I say, well, you know, did I mention some historical fact?
Well, they had no idea.
So I decided, for whatever reason, that promoting the history of the community
pull out the facts and say, hey, this is something to be proud of.
This is our roots.
You know, this is where we started over here was an artesian well, and there was nothing over here at all.
And what the community is, is what the people have made it today.
We're sort of in a, you're running down the highway, you've got lead vehicle, you've got rear vehicle, you're in the middle, you call the rocket ship.
Well, we're sort of in the rocket ship.
We've got Houston,
And when you think of a historical community, Williamsburg or something like that, they're hundreds of years old.
Galveston is almost 200 years old.
And they have grown up, and they got to a point, and they started appreciating their history, and they started developing their culture.
And then they've gone through another generation of that.
When Pasadena, 1895, started, we didn't really get going until 1937.
We've just really started.
We haven't built the historical structures in this community
We're built in Williamsburg.
We're built in Houston.
Houston is 100 years old.
The houses that you see, they're preserving.
We're built.
We haven't gotten to that point.
You look at their evolution, and you go through survival, and when you get into the next generation, then they want something a little bit better.
Capacity has just now gotten to that point.
And I'm trying to say, okay, we've gone through that cycle.
Look at our history.
Take some pride in where we've come from.
And we're also now ready to take a little more responsibility toward that.
quality of life in our community.
Our own cultural, entertainment, social needs need to be satisfied within the community.
No longer are we going to Houston for that good restaurant.
Because I take my wife out a couple times a week.
I don't want to go to Houston.
I want to go to Pasadena.
And I don't want to eat at the same hamburger place every time.
So I'm pleased to see that we're beginning to do it.

On the historical side, I got involved in the Historical Society and helped set up the historical collection that passed in the public library so that that material is available for the public to come in and look at.
Here to fall, if the school should assign to their students, you know, do a history paper, there was no place for them to go.
They might go interview someone they'd heard about, but that was the extent of it.
There was no places they could look at pictures, they could listen to history tapes, which we haven't done yet, by the way, but we're going to.
There was no access to this material.
Also, the early historical materials that were collected, like I said, there's a palm oil collection that I had.
There was a historical society.
There was an early settlers association, which I'm also a member of, collection.
And then there was another collection over here.
And they each kept them private unto themselves because, you know, I don't like someone's out there in that other group.
And I might as well let them look at my stuff.
So by moving to the library, we had created a neutral territory.
The historical collection there in the two years it's existed has quadrupled in size.
If I can ever get mine organized, I'm going to get mine over there too.
But I've been involved in the historical thing.
I'm culturally involved.
I'm through the chamber on the Cultural Affairs Committee.
I was one of the original directors for passing a program on it, which then became a member of the Cultural Affairs Committee.
The Cultural Affairs Committee was the first pulling together of the various culturally oriented
activities in the community.

We have Pasadena Art League is a member, we have the Pasadena City Jazz Ballet is a member, the Pasadena Philharmonic, Pasadena Little Theater, there's several other groups, I can't remember the names, that are involved.
And now we've got such a place for us to talk about.
This is where the Little Theater tells the Philharmonic, you know, well gee, we've been here a long time, but we don't have the support
you've got, would you help us build our membership?
So we can work back and forth with each other.

As an outgrowth of that, we're in the process of forming, we're not sure what we're going to call it, but it'll be something like the Pasadena Cultural Arts Council, which will be a non-profit organization so you can make donations and take it as a tax deduction, where we can funnel, we can hire full-time
coordinator so that it's not going to have to depend upon volunteers, that there's a central place that you can call to get program information, ticket information, this type of thing.
Pasadena Little Theater just recently lost their structure for theaters on fire.
And so they're looking for a new place.
And we said, well, look, if you're going to look for a new place, why don't you get something large enough to accommodate some of these other activities that take.
Philharmonic needs a place.
The Art League needs a place to show their stuff.
So we decided we would try to find some sort of cultural center that we could come up with.
And one of the other hats I wear, one of the other groups involved in the Cultural Affairs Committee is the Historical Society.
And they said, hey, let's save some historical building and what can we use?
And someone came up with, well, it's not that old.
The Capitan Theater is
one of the last of the Art Deco brand movie theaters left.
It was built right at the end.
The guy that built it wasn't reading his paper, and he didn't know the television was coming.
And he put all this money into a really nice place, really, as far as Pasadena, boy, it's one of the outstanding architectural structures.
So we thought, well, let's put together all these various interests and see if we can acquire that structure, renovate it, bring it back to its former glory, and provide it with a home
for all these various groups.
We can also attract in a group from the Texas Ballet Group.
I forgot their full name, but anyway, they're an accredited state ballet group out of Deer Park.
And have them in there, because they're looking for a place.
And there's several musical groups down in Clear Lake.
I'm sure that if we could provide them with a home, we'd then concentrate it and provide a central source for the local community to go.
And it's got all this great attributes, easy access, existing structure, bringing us identity.
And we can go after historical funds, cultural funds.
They're all over the place.
And then we can start programs where school children can go and participate in a full philharmonic and get musical appreciation on a formal level, teaching.
I buy some artwork from some local dealers.
those types of things.
One other, I don't know, cultural, let me expand it slightly.
Again, I mentioned quality of life in the community.
Tom was involved.
My wife is currently in retirement, but was the original director of the Pasadena Beautification Commission.
And Pasadena is in great need of beautification.
I think that adds to
the community's image, quality of life, and cultural appreciation.
Because if you live in a Japanese city, it's really hard to sit there and appreciate something, take pride in it.
Looking back over the four generations of the Pomeroy family, how is your life different than that of your ancestors, and do you have the impact on Pasadena that they once had?
Well, I move a lot faster than my ancestors.
